name: r-ddpcr
raw_meta_yaml:
{% set version = '1.15' %}
{% set posix = 'm2-' if win else '' %}
{% set native = 'm2w64-' if win else '' %}

package:
  name: r-ddpcr
  version: {{ version|replace("-", "_") }}

source:
  url:
    - {{ cran_mirror }}/src/contrib/ddpcr_{{ version }}.tar.gz
    - {{ cran_mirror }}/src/contrib/Archive/ddpcr/ddpcr_{{ version }}.tar.gz
  sha256: 9ad78906d8aec5ca0f57f403d15a2f09e913a726686515cd4b1d8fa7a6990213

build:
  merge_build_host: True  # [win]
  number: 1
  noarch: generic
  rpaths:
    - lib/R/lib/
    - lib/

requirements:
  build:
    - {{ posix }}zip               # [win]
    - cross-r-base {{ r_base }}    # [build_platform != target_platform]
  host:
    - r-base
    - r-dt >=0.2
    - r-dplyr >=0.5.0
    - r-ggplot2 >=2.2.0
    - r-lazyeval >=0.1.10
    - r-magrittr >=1.5
    - r-mixtools >=1.0.2
    - r-plyr >=1.8.1
    - r-readr >=0.1.0
    - r-shiny >=0.11.0
    - r-shinyjs >=0.4.0
    - r-tibble
  run:
    - r-base
    - r-dt >=0.2
    - r-dplyr >=0.5.0
    - r-ggplot2 >=2.2.0
    - r-lazyeval >=0.1.10
    - r-magrittr >=1.5
    - r-mixtools >=1.0.2
    - r-plyr >=1.8.1
    - r-readr >=0.1.0
    - r-shiny >=0.11.0
    - r-shinyjs >=0.4.0
    - r-tibble

test:
  commands:
    - $R -e "library('ddpcr')"           # [not win]
    - "\"%R%\" -e \"library('ddpcr')\""  # [win]

about:
  home: https://github.com/daattali/ddpcr
  license: MIT
  summary: An interface to explore, analyze, and visualize droplet digital PCR (ddPCR) data in
    R. This is the first non-proprietary software for analyzing two-channel ddPCR data.
    An interactive tool was also created and is available online to facilitate this
    analysis for anyone who is not comfortable with using R.
  license_family: MIT
  license_file:
    - '{{ environ["PREFIX"] }}/lib/R/share/licenses/MIT'
    - LICENSE

extra:
  recipe-maintainers:
    - conda-forge/r

# Package: ddpcr

# Authors@R: c( person("Dean", "Attali", email = "daattali@gmail.com", role = c("aut", "cre")) )
# Description: An interface to explore, analyze, and visualize droplet digital PCR (ddPCR) data in R. This is the first non-proprietary software for analyzing two-channel ddPCR data. An interactive tool was also created and is available online to facilitate this analysis for anyone who is not comfortable with using R.
